  en: [
    {
      icon:'💡', color:'#7c3aed',
      title:'Arbitrage Basics',
      subtitle:'What it is and how it works',
      lessons: [
        {
          icon:'📖', title:'What is Crypto Arbitrage?',
          body:`
            <p>Arbitrage is one of the oldest trading strategies. The idea is simple: <strong>buy cheaper in one place and sell more expensive in another</strong>.</p>

            <div class="edu-example">
Regular market:
Apples at market A → $0.50/kg
Apples at market B → $0.70/kg
Profit → $0.20/kg (40%)
            </div>

            <p>In crypto it's the same, but instead of markets — exchanges, and instead of apples — Bitcoin, Ethereum and other coins.</p>

            <div class="edu-example">
Crypto Arbitrage:
BTC on Binance  → $67,234
BTC on Bybit    → $67,891
Difference      → $657 (0.97%)
            </div>

            <p>The main advantage over regular trading — <strong>no market risk</strong>. You don't care which way the price goes, you profit from the difference between exchanges right now.</p>

            <div class="edu-tip">💡 Arbitrage exists because the market is imperfect — different exchanges have different users, different supply and demand.</div>
          `
        },
        {
          icon:'🔍', title:'Why Are Prices Different on Exchanges?',
          body:`
            <p>Many beginners wonder: if Bitcoin is one, why are prices different? Here are the reasons:</p>

            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">1</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>Different liquidity</strong> — millions trade on Binance, thousands on smaller exchanges. Higher volume = more accurate price.</div></div>

            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">2</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>Different geography</strong> — Asian exchanges may react to news faster than European ones.</div></div>

            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">3</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>Different market makers</strong> — each exchange has its own liquidity providers with different prices.</div></div>

            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">4</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>Arbitrageur delay</strong> — while bots equalize prices, a temporary difference forms.</div></div>

            <div class="edu-tip">💡 The smaller the exchange and the less popular the coin — the larger the price discrepancies.</div>
            <div class="edu-warning">⚠️ Spreads last seconds or minutes. You need to act fast!</div>
          `
        },
        {
          icon:'📊', title:'Types of Arbitrage',
          body:`
            <p>There are several types of arbitrage. Each has its pros and cons:</p>

            <p><strong>1. Cross-Exchange (CEX-CEX)</strong></p>
            <p>Buy on one centralized exchange, sell on another.</p>
            <div class="edu-example">Binance → Bybit → OKX → KuCoin</div>
            <p>✅ Simple | ✅ Fast | ❌ Small spread (0.1-0.5%)</p>

            <br><p><strong>2. CEX-DEX Arbitrage</strong></p>
            <p>Buy on centralized exchange, sell on decentralized (or vice versa).</p>
            <div class="edu-example">Binance → Uniswap (Ethereum)
Binance → Raydium (Solana)</div>
            <p>✅ Larger spread (0.5-3%) | ❌ Need wallet | ❌ Gas fees</p>

            <br><p><strong>3. Triangular Arbitrage</strong></p>
            <p>Trade three pairs on one exchange.</p>
            <div class="edu-example">BTC → ETH → USDT → BTC</div>
            <p>✅ No transfers between exchanges | ❌ More complex to calculate</p>

            <br><p><strong>4. Funding Arbitrage</strong></p>
            <p>Earn funding rate payments from futures.</p>
            <p>✅ Stable income | ✅ Minimal risk | ❌ Needs capital</p>

            <div class="edu-tip">💡 LunarBit supports CEX-CEX and CEX-DEX arbitrage. Funding alerts — coming soon!</div>
          `
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      icon:'📊', color:'#0891b2',
      title:'Market Analysis',
      subtitle:'How to read data and choose trades',
      lessons: [
        {
          icon:'📈', title:'How to Read a Spread?',
          body:`
            <p>Spread — the price difference between two exchanges, expressed as a percentage.</p>

            <div class="edu-example">
Formula:
Spread = (Sell Price - Buy Price) / Buy Price × 100%

Example:
Buy ETH on Binance:  $3,450
Sell ETH on Bybit:   $3,484
Spread = (3484 - 3450) / 3450 × 100% = 0.99%
            </div>

            <p><strong>What spread is considered good?</strong></p>

            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">❌</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>0.0 - 0.2%</strong> — unprofitable. Fees will eat everything.</div></div>
            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">⚠️</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>0.2 - 0.4%</strong> — minimal profit. Risk not justified.</div></div>
            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">✅</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>0.4 - 0.8%</strong> — good opportunity. Worth considering.</div></div>
            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">🔥</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>0.8%+</strong> — excellent opportunity. Act fast!</div></div>

            <div class="edu-warning">⚠️ Always subtract fees! Typical fees: 0.1% buy + 0.1% sell = 0.2% total.</div>
          `
        },
        {
          icon:'🎯', title:'How to Choose a Coin?',
          body:`
            <p>Not all coins are equally suitable for arbitrage. Here are the selection criteria:</p>

            <p><strong>✅ Good candidates:</strong></p>
            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">1</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>High trading volume</strong> — minimum $10M/day. You'll be able to buy and sell quickly.</div></div>
            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">2</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>Listed on 3+ exchanges</strong> — more exchanges = more arbitrage opportunities.</div></div>
            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">3</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>Open withdrawal</strong> — the coin must be freely withdrawable on both exchanges.</div></div>
            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">4</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>Fast network</strong> — Solana (0.4 sec), BSC (3 sec) better than Ethereum (15 sec+).</div></div>

            <p><strong>❌ Avoid:</strong></p>
            <p>• New coins (listed less than 3 months ago)</p>
            <p>• Coins with restricted withdrawal</p>
            <p>• Illiquid tokens (volume less than $1M/day)</p>

            <div class="edu-tip">💡 Best coins to start: BTC, ETH, SOL, BNB, XRP — high liquidity, fast withdrawal.</div>
          `
        },
        {
          icon:'⏰', title:'When to Trade?',
          body:`
            <p>Timing matters. Spreads vary at different times of day and market conditions.</p>

            <p><strong>🔥 Best times for arbitrage:</strong></p>

            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">1</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>During volatility</strong> — when price moves sharply, exchanges can't synchronize fast enough. Spreads increase.</div></div>

            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">2</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>Asian session (18:00-02:00 UTC)</strong> — Asian exchanges are active, Western ones sleep. Price gaps are higher.</div></div>

            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">3</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>After major news</strong> — regulation, hardfork, listing news creates temporary imbalances.</div></div>

            <div class="edu-example">
Example: Token listing news on Coinbase
Before: $1.20 (all exchanges)
After on Coinbase: $1.45 (+20%)
Other exchanges: $1.22 (+1.6%)
Arbitrage: buy everywhere → sell on Coinbase
            </div>

            <div class="edu-tip">💡 Use /monitor in LunarBit — the bot works 24/7 and catches opportunities while you sleep!</div>
          `
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      icon:'💰', color:'#059669',
      title:'Capital Management',
      subtitle:'Money, risks and profit calculation',
      lessons: [
        {
          icon:'💵', title:'How Much Capital Do You Need?',
          body:`
            <p>One of the most common questions. Honest answer: <strong>depends on your goal</strong>.</p>

            <div class="edu-example">
Minimum to start:      $200-500
Comfortable trading:   $1,000-5,000
Serious income:        $10,000+
Professional level:    $50,000+
            </div>

            <p><strong>Why is small capital unprofitable?</strong></p>

            <p>With 0.5% spread and $200 capital:</p>
            <div class="edu-example">
Gross profit:     $200 × 0.5% = $1.00
Fees:             $200 × 0.2% = $0.40
Network transfer: $0.50-2.00
Net profit:       -$0.90 ... $0.10 ❌
            </div>

            <p>With 0.5% spread and $5,000 capital:</p>
            <div class="edu-example">
Gross profit:  $5,000 × 0.5% = $25.00
Fees:          $5,000 × 0.2% = $10.00
Transfer:      $0.50-2.00
Net profit:    $13-14.50 ✅
            </div>

            <div class="edu-tip">💡 Start with $500-1000 for learning. Once you understand the mechanics — scale up.</div>
            <div class="edu-warning">⚠️ Never use borrowed funds for arbitrage! Even small delays can lead to losses.</div>
          `
        },
        {
          icon:'🧮', title:'Calculating Real Profit',
          body:`
            <p>Many beginners only count the spread, forgetting costs. Here's the full formula:</p>

            <div class="edu-example">
Full profit formula:

Profit = Capital × (Spread% - Buy Fee% - Sell Fee% - Transfer Cost%)

Typical fees:
• Binance Spot:  0.1% (with BNB: 0.075%)
• Bybit Spot:    0.1%
• OKX Spot:      0.1%
• KuCoin Spot:   0.1%
• MEXC Spot:     0.0% (!)
• Gate.io Spot:  0.2%
            </div>

            <div class="edu-tip">💡 Use fast networks for transfers: Solana ($0.001), BSC ($0.10), Arbitrum ($0.05). Avoid Ethereum mainnet!</div>
          `
        },
        {
          icon:'📋', title:'Risk Management',
          body:`
            <p>Arbitrage is considered low-risk but risks exist. Here's how to manage them:</p>

            <p><strong>Rule 1: Don't keep everything on one exchange</strong></p>
            <div class="edu-example">
Correct allocation:
• Binance: 30%
• Bybit: 30%
• OKX: 20%
• Reserve: 20%
            </div>

            <p><strong>Rule 2: Limit per trade</strong></p>
            <p>Don't risk more than 20-30% of capital in one trade.</p>

            <p><strong>Rule 3: Always check withdrawal before trading</strong></p>
            <p>If withdrawal is closed — arbitrage is impossible!</p>

            <p><strong>Rule 4: Consider transfer time</strong></p>
            <div class="edu-example">
BTC (Bitcoin network): 10-60 min
ETH (ERC20): 2-15 min
SOL (Solana): 10-30 sec
BNB (BSC): 1-3 min
            </div>

            <div class="edu-warning">⚠️ Price can change during transfer. Slower network = higher risk!</div>
          `
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      icon:'📋', color:'#d97706',
      title:'Step-by-Step Guide',
      subtitle:'How to execute your first trade',
      lessons: [
        {
          icon:'⚡', title:'Executing CEX-CEX Arbitrage',
          body:`
            <p>Step-by-step guide to executing a trade:</p>

            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">1</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>Find an opportunity</strong> via LunarBit. Example: SOL +0.8% (Binance→Bybit)</div></div>
            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">2</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>Verify it's still valid.</strong> Spreads live seconds. Check both exchanges to confirm prices are still different.</div></div>
            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">3</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>Calculate profit.</strong> Use LunarBit calculator. If net profit is positive — act!</div></div>
            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">4</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>Buy on the exchange with lower price.</strong> Use Market order for speed, not Limit!</div></div>
            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">5</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>Immediately sell on the exchange with higher price.</strong></div></div>
            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">6</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>Transfer coins between exchanges</strong> to restore balance. Choose fastest, cheapest network.</div></div>

            <div class="edu-example">
Pro tip:
Keep a reserve of coins on BOTH exchanges.
Then you don't need to wait for transfers!

Example:
• On Binance: $1000 USDT + 3 SOL
• On Bybit: $1000 USDT + 3 SOL

Found SOL spread Binance→Bybit:
1. Buy SOL on Binance (spend USDT)
2. Sell SOL on Bybit (get USDT)
Profit is instant!
            </div>
          `
        },
        {
          icon:'🦊', title:'Common Beginner Mistakes',
          body:`
            <p>Learn from others' mistakes:</p>

            <p><strong>❌ Mistake 1: Not accounting for fees</strong></p>
            <p>0.3% spread looks attractive, but after 0.2% fees only 0.1% remains. Almost nothing.</p>
            <div class="edu-warning">Minimum profitable spread: 0.4-0.5%</div>

            <p><strong>❌ Mistake 2: Using Limit orders</strong></p>
            <p>A Limit order might not fill while you wait — price moves away. Use Market orders!</p>

            <p><strong>❌ Mistake 3: Not checking withdrawal status</strong></p>
            <p>You bought the coin but withdrawal is closed for maintenance. Funds frozen!</p>

            <p><strong>❌ Mistake 4: Panic during price movement</strong></p>
            <p>While transferring coins the price may drop. If you hedge (hold reserves on both exchanges) — it doesn't matter.</p>

            <p><strong>❌ Mistake 5: Ignoring slow networks</strong></p>
            <p>BTC transfer can take an hour. The spread disappears and may reverse.</p>

            <p><strong>❌ Mistake 6: Too small capital</strong></p>
            <p>With $100, network fees ($1-5) eat all income.</p>

            <p><strong>❌ Mistake 7: Trading without monitoring</strong></p>
            <p>Good opportunities appear rarely and live seconds. Without automatic monitoring (like LunarBit) you'll miss most trades.</p>
          `
        }
      ]
    },
