      subtitle:'Protecting capital and accounts',
      lessons: [
        {
          icon:'🛡️', title:'All Types of Arbitrage Risks',
          body:`
            <p>Arbitrage is safer than trading, but risks exist:</p>

            <p><strong>1. Price Risk (Execution)</strong></p>
            <p>While you buy on exchange A and sell on exchange B — price changes.</p>
            <div class="edu-example">
Found: Binance $67,234 → Bybit $67,891 (+0.97%)
Bought on Binance at $67,234
During withdrawal — Bybit price fell to $67,100
Result: LOSS -$134
            </div>
            <p>Solution: two-sided arbitrage (hold reserves on both exchanges)</p>

            <br><p><strong>2. Liquidity Risk</strong></p>
            <p>Small exchange may not have buyers at the right price.</p>
            <p>Solution: only trade top-20 coins on major exchanges.</p>

            <br><p><strong>3. Exchange Risk</strong></p>
            <p>Exchange may freeze withdrawals, get hacked or go bankrupt.</p>
            <div class="edu-warning">⚠️ Example: FTX went bankrupt in 2022. Billions frozen.</div>
            <p>Solution: don't keep more than 20-30% of capital on one exchange.</p>

            <br><p><strong>4. Technical Risk</strong></p>
            <p>Internet disconnected during a trade. Exchange API not working.</p>
            <p>Solution: stable internet, backup connection.</p>
          `
        },
        {
          icon:'🔐', title:'Account Security',
          body:`
            <p>Your money is safe only if your accounts are protected:</p>

            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">1</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>Two-Factor Authentication (2FA)</strong> — mandatory! Use Google Authenticator or Authy. SMS is unreliable.</div></div>
            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">2</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>Unique password</strong> — different password for each exchange. Use a password manager.</div></div>
            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">3</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>Withdrawal whitelist</strong> — only allow withdrawal to verified addresses.</div></div>
            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">4</div><div class="edu-step-text"><strong>Separate email</strong> — create a dedicated email only for exchanges.</div></div>

            <div class="edu-tip">💡 Always verify the exchange URL! Phishing sites look identical to real ones.</div>
            <div class="edu-warning">⚠️ Never enter your wallet seed phrase on websites! It's always a scam.</div>
          `
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      icon:'🚀', color:'#7c3aed',
      title:'Advanced Level',
      subtitle:'Strategies for experienced traders',
      lessons: [
        {
          icon:'💎', title:'Funding Arbitrage',
          body:`
            <p>Funding arbitrage is one of the most stable strategies in crypto.</p>

            <p><strong>What is funding?</strong></p>
            <p>On futures exchanges, every 8 hours a "funding" payment occurs — a mechanism to align futures price with spot. Long traders pay short traders (or vice versa).</p>

            <div class="edu-example">
BTC funding rate: +0.03% every 8 hours
= +0.09% per day
= +2.7% per month
= +32.4% per year (!)
            </div>

            <p><strong>Strategy:</strong></p>
            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">1</div><div class="edu-step-text">Buy BTC on spot (hedge position)</div></div>
            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">2</div><div class="edu-step-text">Open same-size short on futures</div></div>
            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">3</div><div class="edu-step-text">Collect funding every 8 hours</div></div>
            <div class="edu-step"><div class="edu-step-num">4</div><div class="edu-step-text">Market risk is neutralized — BTC price doesn't matter!</div></div>

            <div class="edu-tip">💡 LunarBit will soon add high funding rate alerts! Stay tuned.</div>
            <div class="edu-warning">⚠️ Risk: funding can go negative — then you pay. Watch the rates!</div>
          `
        }
      ]
    }
